The history of Bitcoin is full of curiosities and interesting facts. You can easily search and discover infinite stories over these 15 years.
I decided to bring some of these facts and events.
I tried to list them in chronological order, although some facts cannot be dated.
 
1.
You may have asked yourself several times throughout this book: Who is Satoshi Nakamoto? Satoshi Nakamoto was the pseudonym chosen by the individual or group of individuals who brought together various existing technologies to create Bitcoin. There has been extensive speculation and many theories have been proposed regarding the true identity of this figure. I am not going to get into the debate of the myriads of speculations about who they might be, as there is a wealth of texts, videos, and articles on the subject. What is crucial to recognize is that beyond Satoshi's genius in creating Bitcoin, his most significant accomplishment was arguably his ability to disappear.
2.
On August 18, 2008, the domain address www.bitcoin.org was registered. It utilized a service based in Japan known as Anonymous Speech, which permits the anonymous purchase of domain addresses. This choice underscores the creators of Bitcoin's emphasis on privacy.
3.
On October 31, 2008, Bitcoin was introduced to the world through a document titled 'Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System'. Authored by an individual or group using the pseudonym Satoshi Nakamoto (email: satoshin@gmx.com), the whitepaper was shared on the cryptography mailing list hosted by metzdowd.com, a platform renowned among cypherpunk groups for its engagement with cryptographic innovations. This nine-page academic-style paper, complete with an abstract, introduction, and conclusion, was more than just a proposal, it was the beginning of the Bitcoin project which is based on cryptographic principles and an alternative trust mechanism that does not require trusted third parties.
https://bitcoin.org/bitcoin.pdf 
4.
It is not known exactly when Satoshi began working on the Bitcoin project, but on January 3, 2009, the genesis block of Bitcoin was mined. Along with the first block (block 0), the first bitcoins were created: 50 more precisely, which were paid to the block miner, who in this case was Satoshi.
However, the Genesis block contains some curiosities. The address to which the 50 bitcoins from the coinbase transaction were sent is not part of the blockchain. It is unknown whether it was on purpose or a mistake, but Satoshi decided not to add the coinbase transaction from the genesis block to the global transaction database. Thus, all the nodes in the network would reject the block. Therefore, the bitcoins that are at this address can never be used.
Along with the block's only transaction (coinbase transaction), Satoshi included a message in the block: "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks".
Satoshi never explained this. However, it is believed that one of Satoshi's aims in creating Bitcoin might have been to help people from having to hand money over to a bank as an alternative to stashing cash under their mattresses. In 2009, the Great Recession was in full swing. Some people had gone to their bank only to find their money was gone. Other people found their pensions had gone the same way. Many think it is no coincidence that Satoshi chose that particular headline to write into the Genesis Block. This was supposed to be the beginning of the end of people relying on banks so much that the government had to rescue them from their own mistakes using taxpayers' money.
Another theory is that the inclusion of a headline from that day proves that the hash could not have been generated before that day. 
It is also curious that the second Bitcoin block was mined on January 9, a full six days after the first one. Typically, Bitcoin blocks are designed to be mined every 10 minutes. This delay for the second block could be attributed to various reasons. The algorithm responsible for adjusting the mining difficulty to maintain the 10-minute interval only activates approximately every two weeks, so Satoshi may have deliberately waited to mine more blocks because he waited to see if other people joined the network. He didn't want to premise it all to himself.
Another theory says that as he was the only one mining at that time, and still needed to make adjustments to the code and use the computer daily, there was little time available for his computer to be dedicated to mining, which took longer.
Another theory is that Satoshi's original Bitcoin version would only start mining if it had at least one more peer so it is possible that Satoshi's node was running when publishing the software but only started mining when a second peer joined the network. Bitcoin 0.1 was only announced to the mailing list on the 8th of January at 19:27 UTC, and then the second node would have only appeared on the network once someone else's interest was piqued enough to download and run the software. Block 1 (the second block) is timestamped 2009-01-09 2:54 UTC, 7 hours and 27 minutes after the email announcement.
However, a more intriguing theory suggests that Satoshi deliberately chose to mirror the six days it took for God to create the world, as described in the Book of Genesis.
https://mempool.space/tx/4a5e1e4baab89f3a32518a88c31bc87f618f76673e2cc77ab2127b7afdeda33b 
https://www.thetimes03jan2009.com/ 
 
5.
Bitcoin v0.1, the first software version, was released on January 8, 2009. From that moment on, the code became available for viewing, downloading, and for anyone to run, in addition to receiving feedback and suggestions for adjustments.
https://www.mail-archive.com/cryptography@metzdowd.com/msg10142.html 
6.
On January 11, 2009, Satoshi's email announcing the first version of Bitcoin was responded to by Hal Finney, congratulating him and saying that he would soon run a node.
In the same answer, Hal already speculates on the value that Bitcoin could obtain if it became the world's reserve asset (despite having mentioned "dominant payment system"): "Then the total value of the currency should be equal to the total value of all the wealth in the world. Current estimates of total worldwide household wealth that I have found range from $100 trillion to $300 trillion. With 20 million coins, that gives each coin a value of about $10 million."
https://www.mail-archive.com/cryptography@metzdowd.com/msg10152.html 
7.
On January 12, 2009, the first recognized Bitcoin transaction occurred, marking a significant milestone for the Bitcoin blockchain. Satoshi Nakamoto sent 10 BTC to Hal Finney, demonstrating the system's ability to facilitate a secure, peer-to-peer, and decentralized transaction. This historic transfer was recorded in block number 170.
https://mempool.space/block/00000000d1145790a8694403d4063f323d499e655c83426834d4ce2f8dd4a2ee 
8.
October 5, 2009: The 'New Liberty Standard' website published the first exchange rate between Bitcoin and the US dollar, offering a service for buying or selling BTC using PayPal. The initial rate was astonishingly set at 1,309.03 BTC to 1 USD, effectively valuing each Bitcoin at approximately $0.000764. Curiously, the BTC fiat price set by New Liberty Standard was determined not by buying or selling trading activity, but by the price of
electricity and the website owner's personal BTC mining output: "Our exchange rate is calculated by dividing $1.00 by the average amount of electricity required to run a computer with high CPU for a year, 1331.5 kWh, multiplied by the average residential cost of electricity in the United States for the previous year, $0.1136, divided by 12 months divided by the number of bitcoins generated by my computer over the past 30 days."
https://newlibertystandard.io/exchange 
https://web.archive.org/web/20091229132610/http://newlibertystandard.wetpaint.com/page/Exchange+Rate 
9.
On October 12, 2009, Finnish developer Martti 'Sirius' Malmi, one of Bitcoin's first developers, made the first recorded BTC to fiat currency exchange. He sold 5,050 BTC for US$5.02 using PayPal through the New Liberty Standard exchange service. This sale valued each Bitcoin at approximately US$0.000994. The transaction is included in block number 24,835. This was the first time Bitcoin was exchanged for a government-issued currency.
https://twitter.com/marttimalmi/status/423455561703624704 
10. 
Satoshi would like to make some of the features of version 0.2 available on a forum to collect responses and feedback. Therefore, after some email exchanges with Martti Malmi debating which platform to use, they decided on https://bitcoin.org/smf  on 20 November 2009.
The location of the forum migrated to https://forum.bitcoin.org  later.
https://mmalmi.github.io/satoshi/ 
11.
December 16, 2009: Bitcoin Version 0.2 is released just a few months after the initial release. This update introduced a Linux version. This release was achieved with the help of Martti Malmi (nickname Sirius), one of Bitcoin's earliest developers and contributors. 
https://www.bitcoin.com/satoshi-archive/forum/bitcoin-forum/21/#selection-25.0-25.40 
https://www.bitcoin.com/satoshi-archive/emails/bitcoin-list/11/ 
12.
Although block difficulty is adjusted every 2016 block, the first difficulty adjustment occurred at block 32,256 on December 30, 2009. Before that, the average time to mine a block was over 10 minutes (between block 1 and block 32,256, the average block time was 16 minutes), and the retarget adjustment algorithm only works if block times are under 10 minutes.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=5363163.msg58058198#msg58058198 
 
13.
On January 15, 2010, dwdollar (Dustin Dollar) announced on the 'Bitcoin Forum' that he had begun creating an alternative to the New Liberty Standard (NLS) exchange service. He said he was building an exchange that would be a real market where people could buy and sell Bitcoins with each other, reflecting real trading between market participants, rather than relying on calculations based on the electricity cost for mining and other factors.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=20.0 
14.
On March 17, 2010, dwdollar delivered what he promised: Bitcoin Market, the first exchange with BTC buy and sell orders went live at www.bitcoinmarket.com. But recurring problems with fraud led to the payment service PayPal blacklisting the site on June 4, 2011.
https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/696258-first-cryptocurrency-exchange 
15.
On May 18, 2010, one of the most folkloric and remembered facts happened within the Bitcoin community: Laszlo Hanyecz, a programmer in Jacksonville, Florida, offered to pay 10,000 BTC for someone to deliver two pizzas to his house. He created the following thread on the 'Bitcoin Forum' titled 'Pizza for Bitcoin?':
"I'd like to buy a couple of large pizzas for 10,000 bitcoins. I hope to have some leftovers for the next day because I enjoy nibbling on pizza later. You can either make the pizzas yourself and bring them to my house, or you can order them for me from a delivery place. What I'm looking for is to exchange bitcoins for food delivery without having to order or prepare it myself. It's like ordering a 'breakfast platter' at a hotel where they bring you something to eat and you're happy!"
I like things like onions, peppers, sausage, mushrooms, tomatoes, pepperoni, etc. just standard stuff no weird fish topping or anything like that.  I also like regular cheese pizzas which may be cheaper to prepare or otherwise acquire.
If you're interested please let me know and we can work out a deal.
Thanks,
Laszlo"
Laszlo reported that on May 22, 2010, he had successfully traded 10,000 BTC for two pizzas. Jeremy Sturdivant accepted the BTC and ordered the pizzas from Papa John's for delivery to Laszlo's home, where he received them the same day.
And there's one more curiosity in this story: If it was Papa John's or Domino? Not even Jeremy himself remembers.
Excerpt from an interview with him:
"Q. This Bitcoin wiki page says Laszlo bought two Domino pizzas from you, but the pictures are of Papa John's, what do you remember?
A. I'm starting to regret not keeping chat logs of the event, as I clearly remember Domino's pizza (right down to their particular web interface), but the pictures show Papa John's."
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=137.0 
https://web.archive.org/web/20120506074339/http://heliacal.net/~solar/bitcoin/pizza/ 
https://www.bitcoinwhoswho.com/blog/2018/05/08/the-first-bitcoin-transaction-was-it-for-two-dominos-or-papajohns-pizza/ 
16.
You may be wondering how Laszlo managed to collect 10 thousand bitcoins when, at the time, almost no purchase and sale transactions were being made, and most were obtained through mining. The answer is mining with graphics cards. Until then, bitcoin mining was performed using traditional computer processors (CPUs). However, Laszlo discovered a method to mine using the computational capacity of video processors (GPUs). He shared this innovation on the Bitcointalk forum on May 10, 201, just a few days before posting about the iconic pizza. This suggests that he was already mining with significantly greater capacity than other miners and, consequently, generating more blocks and receiving more reward bitcoins.
Years later, in an interview, Laszlo revealed that he received an email from Satoshi asking him to be careful with such mining.
Satoshi's concern was with the decentralization of the network in the early years. He wanted anyone to be able to be part of the network and mine with their laptop.
After apologizing, Laszlo received a response telling him to just not encourage it and let the post die.
Later, Satoshi would have shared with Laszlo the fact that he had already developed mining for GPU before, precisely to have a defense mechanism in case a 51% attack occurred. But he would have agreed that Laszlo's code was more optimized for Bitcoin.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=133.0 
https://www.bitcoin.com/satoshi-archive/emails/laszlo-hanec/1/ 
https://hashrateindex.com/blog/bitcoin-pizza-day-gpu-mining/ 
https://cointelegraph.com/news/satoshi-invented-gpu-mining-to-defend-the-network-says-early-dev 
17.
On May 28, 2010, Gavin Andresen, one of the early Bitcoin adopters, created a Bitcoin faucet in an attempt to help the Bitcoin project succeed. This site allowed anyone to simply enter their Bitcoin address, solve a captcha, and receive 5 bitcoins. He explained that this would provide a way for people to obtain bitcoins without waiting for their node to mine a block. Initially, he funded the faucet with 1,100 bitcoins, and additional donations were made by others. Ultimately, the faucet distributed 19,700 BTC before it closed in 2012.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=183.0 
https://web.archive.org/web/20100703032414/ http://freebitcoins.appspot.com/ 
18.
On July 17, 2010, Mt. Gox launched as a Bitcoin exchange, originally developed by programmer Jed McCaleb. Initially designed as a platform for trading 'Magic: The Gathering Online' cards, the site pivoted to support the growing interest in Bitcoin, becoming the largest Bitcoin exchange by market share and handling about 70% of all transactions in 2013.
The name "Mt. Gox" stands for "Magic: The Gathering Online Exchange," reflecting its origins.
On March 6, 2011, McCaleb sold Mt. Gox to Tibanne, a company owned by Mark Karpelès in Japan. Despite its significant market presence, Mt. Gox collapsed in February 2014 due to security and management issues.
https://www.wired.com/2014/03/bitcoin-exchange/ 
https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/mt-gox.asp 
19.
On August 9th, 2010, the first big Bitcoin loss occurred. A Bitcointalk forum member, Stone Man, posted on August 10th that he couldn't find 8,999 of his bitcoins. This loss was due to a misunderstanding of how UTXO and the wallet mechanism he was using worked. He attempted to send himself 1 out of the 9,000 bitcoins he had, but he didn't indicate the change address. As a result, the wallet sent the 'change' (8,999 bitcoins) to an address for which he did not have the private keys.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=782.0 
 
20.
The Bitcoin Network block 74638, mined on August 15th, 2010, holds a strange record, noted and reported at Bitcointalk Forum by Jeff Garzik. A bug in the Bitcoin code at that time allowed someone to exploit it and generate a massive amount of Bitcoin (184,467,440,737.09 BTCs). This amount was split between two addresses.
Luckily, the situation was identified and addressed quickly. Bitcoin developers, including Satoshi Nakamoto, Gavin Andresen, Jeff Garzik, and Theymos, worked together to fix the bug. This incident, later known as the "value overflow incident", highlighted a vulnerability in how Bitcoin transactions were checked. The code wasn't equipped to handle large outputs that overflowed when summed together before being included in a block.
The response was quick. Within five hours, upgrades to the Bitcoin client were released. Additionally, users quickly adopted new consensus rules that rejected transactions with overflowing output values. This was implemented through a soft fork of the blockchain, a change in the protocol that didn't require a complete split in the network.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=822.0 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=823.0 
21.
The initial Bitcoin logo, released by Satoshi in January 2009 alongside the early version of the Bitcoin wallet client, appeared at the top of the application. It was depicted as a gold coin featuring the letters "B" and "C" in the center.
On February 5, 2010, NewLibertyStandard proposed adopting the Thai Baht currency symbol, ₿, along with the three-letter currency code BTC. Subsequently, on February 24, 2010, Satoshi Nakamoto announced a redesign of the logo, likely incorporating some of these suggestions. The revised logo maintained the "gold coin" appearance but replaced the initials 'B' and 'C' with a central ₿. He also sought feedback on this change.
Finally, on November 1, 2010, a member named Bit Boy posted a new design that was widely approved and has been adopted as the standard ever since. The "gold coin" was replaced with a plain orange circle, and the "₿" logo was tilted 14% clockwise, creating a cleaner and more minimalist style.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=41.0 
https://web.archive.org/web/20130524055823/https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=64.0 
https://web.archive.org/web/20140426192534/https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=1631.0 
22.
On November 8th, 2010, the term 'shitcoin' was first reported about altcoins. The member Ribuck said that if Bitcoin took off, several imitators would appear selling their copies of Bitcoin, such as gitcoin, nitcoin, witcoin, titcoin, and shitcoin.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=1647.msg20646#msg20646 
23.
The term 'satoshi' was proposed as the name for a subdivision of a Bitcoin unit on November 15, 2010, by the member Ribuck. Another proposed name was 'Austrian,' referencing the Austrian School of Economics. The initial proposal did not gain much support, but on February 10, 2011, it was revisited in another discussion about the future need for Bitcoin's divisibility. Finally, the term was accepted by the community after user marcus_of_augustus asked, '100 million satoshis = 1 bitcoin. Are we agreed?' in a third discussion.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=369.msg22160#msg22160 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=3311.msg46648#msg46648 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=3574.msg50647#msg50647 
24.
On 27th November 2010, the Bitcointalk forum member Slush posted that he had designed the first Bitcoin Mining Pool. Before this development, individual miners using CPU-based systems faced intense competition, particularly from those using GPU-enabled computers. The post highlighted the challenges faced by CPU miners, who often struggled to compete with more powerful GPU miners for block rewards.
The member slush proposed a solution to pool the computational power of multiple CPUs together. This approach aimed to increase the chances of finding a block and thereby receiving a proportional reward. By joining the mining pool, CPU miners could enjoy more consistent rewards compared to solo mining, where finding a block could take weeks or even months.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=1976.0 
25.
In early December 2010, donations to Wikileaks via payment methods like PayPal, Mastercard, and VISA were blocked due to the United States diplomatic cables leaks. The Bitcoin community suggested using peer-to-peer transactions to support Wikileaks financially. On December 5, 2010, Satoshi cautioned against Wikileaks using Bitcoin, stating that the project needed gradual growth to strengthen the software. He explained that Bitcoin was still a small beta community and that trying to use it could bring unwanted attention that might harm Bitcoin's development.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=1735.msg26999#msg26999 
26.
On 12th December 2010, Satoshi Nakamoto made his last post on the Bitcoin Forum and later edited that post the next day (13th December). He did not explain the reasons, but it is believed that the fact that Wikileaks had started accepting donations in bitcoins would draw unwanted attention to the project at that time.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=2228.0 
27.
Silk Road was launched in February 2011 by Ross Ulbricht, who operated under the pseudonym "Dread Pirate Roberts." Ulbricht was the primary developer behind the site, although he received assistance from a few others known by the pseudonyms Variety Jones and Smedley for maintaining and promoting the platform. Silk Road was designed as an online black market, primarily used for the sale of illegal drugs, but it also facilitated transactions for other illicit goods and services. The site operated on the Tor network, which provided anonymity to its users, and transactions were conducted using Bitcoin to further obscure the identities of buyers and sellers. Despite its illicit nature, the Silk Road was intended to be a free marketplace where anyone could buy and sell anything they wanted.
Nick Bilton - American Kingpin: The Epic Hunt for the Criminal Mastermind Behind the Silk Road.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silk_Road_(marketplace) 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=3984.msg57080#msg57080 
28.
Despite no longer posting anything on the forum, Satoshi continued to communicate via email with some of the project's developers. On April 23, 2011, Mike Hearn declared that he had received the last email from Satoshi, where he declared that he was dedicating himself to other projects and that with Gavin Andresen and other developers involved, Bitcoin was in good hands. Gavin later stated that the last email he received from Satoshi was on April 26, 2011, in which he again said that he was dedicating himself to new projects, and asked that the community start referring to Bitcoin as an open-source project developed by the community, and not by a mysterious figure.
In his response, Gavin commented that he had accepted an invitation from a government-funded company to speak about Bitcoin at an annual conference on emerging technologies they were hosting and that that year's theme would be "Mobility of Money". The fact that Satoshi never responded demonstrates once again that his goal was for Bitcoin to be seen as an Open Source project, developed and updated by the community.
https://www.bitcoin.com/satoshi-archive/emails/mike-hearn/16/ 
https://gavinandresen.ninja/eleven-years-ago-today 
29.
On June 24th, 2011, the forum migrated from https://forum.bitcoin.org  to https://bitcointalk.org. Later, the 'forum' link was simply removed, further distancing BitcoinTalk from the official www.bitcoin.org website. The forum was originally located at bitcoin.org/smf, then forum.bitcoin.org, and finally bitcointalk.org. Jeff Garzik is credited with inventing the name 'BitcoinTalk,' and he bought the www.bitcointalk.org domain. The forum, which had just changed its name, was at the time, and continued to be, the primary forum for Bitcoin enthusiasts and developers to discuss and where most of the announcements were made over the years. It was also a reference for information and facts for this book.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=971543.msg10607781#msg10607781 
30.
The first Bitcoin tattoo was publicly revealed on July 11, 2011. The artwork was created in a studio in Las Vegas and consists of a gold coin with the Bitcoin symbol. You can research where on the body it was tattooed. Although this was the first publicly exposed tattoo, it's worth noting that another person had tattooed something related to Bitcoin a few days earlier, but only shared it with a few people.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=27958.0 
31.
On August 20th, 2011, the world's first Bitcoin Conference & Expo took place in New York City. The event brought together fewer than 100 Bitcoin enthusiasts, a modest yet passionate group. It was organized by the Bitcoin Center NYC, which has been a hub for discussions and activities related to Bitcoin. Some of the speakers included Gavin Andresen, Jeff Garzik, Stefan Thomas, and Bruce Wagner, who convinced a restaurant in the area to accept payments in Bitcoin. That night, a group went there for dinner, and after everyone had eaten, Wagner asked the members of the group to combine all their payments into a group payment. This was the owner's first time using the system, and everyone there wanted to make it as easy as possible. The experiment didn't work well until Yifu Guo offered to pay for the group with an immediate voucher that he could e-mail from his account with Mt. Gox to the owner of the restaurant. Then everyone else could reimburse him through an Android-based Bitcoin wallet.
https://spectrum.ieee.org/the-worlds-first-bitcoin-conference 
32.
Charlie Lee announced the creation of Litecoin, a fork of Bitcoin. Since Bitcoin's source code is open, anyone can copy it, change some parameters, and run their version. Although it was not the first project of its kind, Litecoin aimed to be digital silver, with Bitcoin as digital gold. The main change was the block mining time of 2.5 minutes, allowing Litecoin to be transacted faster, though it did not guarantee the same security as Bitcoin, according to the founder. The project went live and began running on October 13, 2011.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=47417.0 
https://github.com/litecoin-project/litecoin 
33.
A developer created an online casino called Bitcoin Casino and claimed that the site was generating revenue in BTCs, but he wanted to sell the project due to concerns about legal issues. Erik Voorhees bought the project, renamed it SatoshiDice, and announced the blockchain-based betting game on BitcoinTalk on April 24th, 2012.
SatoshiDice was a simple online dice game that operated on the Bitcoin blockchain. Players bet Bitcoin on the outcome of a dice roll, with different probabilities and payouts available based on the chosen numbers. The game leveraged the transparency and security of blockchain technology to ensure fairness. The game functioned by having players send Bitcoin to a specific address corresponding to their desired bet. The outcome of the dice roll was determined by a cryptographic hash function, ensuring that the results were provably fair and could not be tampered with.
Rumor has it that within a few weeks, the site was already responsible for at least half of all BTC network transactions. In July 2013, Erik Voorhees sold SatoshiDice for 126,315 BTC (worth around $11.5 million at the time).
https://www.reddit.com/r/Bitcoin/comments/segz0/anyone_want_to_run_my_bitcoin_casino/ 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=77870.0 
https://bitcoinmagazine.com/markets/satoshidice-sold-12-4-million 
34.
Bitcoin Magazine was co-founded by Mihai Alisie and Vitalik Buterin. The magazine initially went on sale on May 1, 2012, from its base in South Korea. It was one of the first printed publications exclusively devoted to Bitcoin. Subscribers began to receive the physical copies a few weeks later. In late 2014, Bitcoin Magazine was acquired by BTC Media LLC, an American company based in Nashville, Tennessee.
https://bitcoinmagazine.com/ 
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin_Magazine 
35.
Coinbase officially launched its first product, a simple Bitcoin buying and selling service, in October 2012. The platform had a user-friendly interface, which attracted users who were interested in Bitcoin but found other methods too complex.
The co-founders Brian Armstrong, a former engineer at Airbnb, and Fred Ehrsam, who had experience as a trader at Goldman Sachs met through a Bitcoin subreddit forum.
Coinbase was listed on the NASDAQ stock exchange on April 14, 2021, under the ticker symbol COIN.
And by the way, if you read the book before getting here, you know what "coinbase" means.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coinbase 
36.
The Bitcoin Foundation was launched in September 2012 by Gavin Andresen, Jon Matonis, Patrick Murck, Charlie Shrem, and Peter Vessenes as a nonprofit organization. The foundation's goals included supporting Bitcoin's core development, educating the public about Bitcoin's benefits, and acting with regulatory bodies.
The Membership fee structure in October 2012 was:
Individual Memberships:
Lifetime: 2.7 BTC
Annual: 0.27 BTC
Industry Memberships:
Platinum: 1088.5 BTC
Gold: 272.1 BTC
Silver: Starts at 10.9 BTC
https://www.bitcoinfoundation.org/ 
