37.
On November 28th, 2012, the first Bitcoin Halving event occurred. For the first time, the rewards for mining a Bitcoin block were reduced by half, dropping from 50 BTC to 25 BTC. This event occurs approximately every four years (precisely every 210,000 blocks).
Some interesting facts about this event include:
The total number of Bitcoins in circulation had just hit 10.5 million at that point, which is half of all the Bitcoins that will ever be mined.
The price of one BTC at the time was around USD 12.
The block was mined by the Braiins mining pool (formerly Slush).
It contained 457 transactions.
The block generated 25 BTC plus 13.6 BTC in fees, totaling 38.6 BTC in rewards for the miner.
https://mempool.space/pt/block/000000000000048b95347e83192f69cf0366076336c639f9b7228e9ba171342e 
https://www.theverge.com/2012/11/28/3701434/total-number-of-bitcoins-hits-10-5-million-production-halves-to-stop 
38.
On January 30th, 2013, Jeff Garzik posted in his blog that he had just received a package from China: an ASIC (Application-Specific Integrated Circuit) used for mining Bitcoins. The next day, Garzik shared his mining results, stating, "After 20 hours of mining, the unconfirmed + confirmed rewards equal 14.98832170 BTC. Note that Slush's pool was very lucky recently, in addition to some blocks with abnormally high TX fee income, so that number skews much higher than expected."
https://x.com/jgarzik/status/296709252351926273 
https://garzikrants.blogspot.com/2013/01/avalon-asic-miner-review.html 
39.
At the end of March 11, 2013, a Bitcoin miner running version 0.8 created a large block (at a height of 225,430) that was incompatible with earlier versions of Bitcoin. This caused a fork in the Bitcoin network and resulted in two separate blockchains. In the early hours of the following day, the developer community identified the problem: on February 19th of that same year, version 0.8 of the code had been released. This version included a change in the database system that allowed a greater volume of transactions in each block, which the previous version 0.7 did not support. With the recent increase in transaction volume on the Bitcoin network, some blocks exceeded this limit and were rejected by nodes running version 0.7 but accepted by version 0.8, creating two incompatible blockchains.
Pieter Wuille announced that after discussions, the community recognized that the least risky path was to continue with the old chain. The correction plan included several actions: miners needed to stop using version 0.8 and return to version 0.7, and nodes that had updated to the latest version needed to revert to the previous version. Another recommendation was for merchants to stop accepting Bitcoin payments temporarily to avoid the risk of accepting transactions on the new chain, which would be discarded if the plan succeeded.
The plan worked, and 24 blocks later, the old chain had become the longest chain again.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=145184.0 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=152030.0 
https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/BIP_0050  
40.
On March 19, 2013, Hal Finney wrote a post talking about his journey with Bitcoin over the last 4 years. He had been diagnosed with ALS (Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis) 4 years earlier and at that point, he was already completely paralyzed. The post, as well as all other writings, were made using a commercial eye tracker system.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=155054.0 
41.
On March 28, 2013, the market value of Bitcoin surpassed the 1 billion dollar mark. The price had almost doubled in the last 10 days. One of the explanations was the events taking place in Cyprus. On March 18 of that year, following an escalation of the economic crisis, Cyprus closed all banks due to concerns regarding a likely bank run with a reopening planned for after the scheduled 25 March holiday. This fact would have encouraged not only the inhabitants of Cyprus but also other people in the world concerned about the possibility of a totalitarian government unilaterally blocking their funds to look for a sovereign alternative to store their assets.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012%E2%80%932013_Cypriot_financial_crisis 
42.
On April 18, 2013, Adam Back, the inventor of hash cash, presented himself at Bitcoin talks after, according to him, "24 years of internet use, 18 years of Linux, 30 years of programming". His last activity on the forum was on June 17, 2023.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=15672.msg1873483#msg1873483 
43.
On October 1st, 2013, the Federal Bureau of Investigation arrested Ross Ulbricht at the Glen Park branch of the San Francisco Public Library, accusing him of being the creator of Silk Road. To prevent Ulbricht from encrypting or deleting files on his laptop during the arrest, two agents pretended to be lovers to distract him. When they had sufficiently diverted his attention, they quickly moved in to arrest him. Meanwhile, a third agent grabbed the laptop and handed it to another agent, who then inserted a flash drive into one of the laptop's USB ports, using software to copy key files.
The FBI seized 144,336 bitcoins from a shared digital wallet on Ulbricht's laptop. These were sold in a series of auctions, generating proceeds worth $48.2 million.
Ulbricht was found guilty of each of the seven charges he faced on February 5, 2015, following a four-week jury trial. On May 29, 2015, he was sentenced in Manhattan federal court to life in prison.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_Ulbricht 
https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/acting-manhattan-us-attorney-announces-forfeiture-48-million-sale-silk-road-bitcoins 
https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/ross-ulbricht-aka-dread-pirate-roberts-sentenced-manhattan-federal-court-life-prison 
44.
On October 29th, 2013, the first known publicly available Bitcoin ATM (Automatic Teller Machine) was installed at Waves Coffee House in Vancouver, Canada. The machine was built by a Nevada company called Robocoin. It scans your palm and allows you to buy bitcoins with cash or sell bitcoins for cash.
https://web.archive.org/web/20131101202753/https://mashable.com/2013/10/30/bitcoin-atm-2/ 
https://web.archive.org/web/20200905213625/https://www.wired.com/2013/10/robocoin-here 
45.
Have you ever heard any Bitcoiners talking about HODL? This expression was coined on December 18, 2013, when a user named GameKyuubi made a post on the popular BitcoinTalk forum. He meant to write "I AM HOLDING" to show he wasn't going to sell his coins even though the price had risen dramatically in the last weeks. Instead, he mistyped it and wrote "I AM HODLING." In the post, he mentioned that he had consumed whiskey, although the bottle said "whisky" (without the e). From that moment, Bitcoiners stopped 'holding' their coins and began 'hodling' them.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=375643.0 
46.
The complete story of the Mt. Gox exchange could fill a book. Launched in 2010, it was handling over 70% of all Bitcoin (BTC) buys and sells worldwide by early 2014 when it abruptly ceased operations amid revelations of its involvement in the loss or theft of hundreds of thousands of bitcoins.
On February 7, 2014, Mt. Gox halted all Bitcoin withdrawals. A press release issued on February 10 stated that the issue was due to transaction malleability. According to Gavin Andresen, this feature has been known since 2011. Therefore, any company dealing with Bitcoin transactions and coding their wallet software should have responsibly prepared for this possibility by including a way to validate transaction IDs. Failing to do so could result in Bitcoin loss. Following this incident, all major Bitcoin exchanges suspended withdrawals as well.
By February 17, all other exchanges had returned to normal operations, except for Mt. Gox, which continued to halt withdrawals. On February 20, after a protest by two Bitcoin enthusiasts outside the building housing the Mt. Gox headquarters in Tokyo citing "security concerns," Mt. Gox moved its offices to a different location in Shibuya.
On February 24, Mt. Gox suspended all trading, and its website went offline, returning a blank page. A leaked alleged internal document claimed that the company was insolvent and had lost almost 750,000 BTC in customer funds and another 100,000 BTC of its own.
On February 28, Mt. Gox filed in Tokyo for a form of bankruptcy protection from creditors called minji saisei (civil rehabilitation) to allow courts to seek a buyer.
The Mt. Gox saga continues as of this writing when some of the customers' bitcoins have been paid out.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mt._Gox 
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=4412667.0 
https://www.mtgox.com/img/pdf/20140521_announce.pdf 
https://www.coindesk.com/business/2024/07/05/mt-gox-begins-repayments-in-bitcoin-and-bitcoin-cash/ 
 
47.
On March 6th, 2014, Newsweek Magazine posted an online article titled "The Face Behind Bitcoin," written by Leah McGrath Goodman. It claimed, after months of investigation, to have discovered the identity of Satoshi Nakamoto.
Dorian Satoshi Nakamoto strongly denied being the creator of Bitcoin. In a public statement, he asserted that he had never heard of Bitcoin until his son mentioned it after being contacted by a reporter. He also clarified that he had no involvement in the development of Bitcoin and had never worked on cryptography or similar projects. Nakamoto emphasized that the misidentification had caused him significant stress and disruption to his life.
https://www.newsweek.com/2014/03/14/face-behind-bitcoin-247957.html 
