51.
On March 29, 2017, posts were made from Hal Finney's account on the BitcoinTalk forum. However, Hal Finney, one of the earliest adopters of Bitcoin, passed away on August 28, 2014. Therefore, the posts were made by someone who had hacked his account.
Following the breach, the forum administrator, theymos, promptly locked Finney's account to prevent further unauthorized activity. Theymos explained that he had kept the account unlocked because he thought Finney's family members might want to look at his private messages or other information. However, given the circumstances, it became clear that the account had almost certainly been compromised. The hacker likely gained access via an email password reset, indicating that Finney's email account was also probably compromised.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=1847311.0 
52.
On 20th June 2017, India decided to regulate Bitcoin. After investigations by the Finance Ministry's Inter-Disciplinary Committee, the government ruled in favor of regulation. Indian Bitcoin exchanges like Zebpay and Coinsecure had self-regulated with strict KYC and anti-money laundering systems. Indian exchanges had been processing around 11% of Bitcoin-to-USD trades.
https://cointelegraph.com/news/suddenly-bitcoin-to-be-officially-legal-in-india 
53.
On 1st August 2017, the Bitcoin Cash fork happened. Since Bitcoin's blockchain has a limit on the size of blocks (1 MB per block), there is a limited number of transactions it can process per second. This led to slower transaction times and high fees during peak usage periods. Some in the community believed increasing the block size would allow for faster and cheaper transactions. They proposed raising the limit from 1MB to 8 MB. But for the majority of the Bitcoin community, larger blocks would make it harder for individuals to run nodes on the network, potentially centralizing it. Since no agreement could be reached, a hard fork occurred. This means the Bitcoin blockchain diverged into two separate branches:
Bitcoin (BTC): The original chain remained with the 1MB block size limit.
Bitcoin Cash (BCH): The new chain adopted the 8MB block size. As a result of the fork, anyone holding Bitcoin at the time received the same amount of Bitcoin Cash.
Gavin Andresen, one of the early developers of Bitcoin who took over as the lead developer of Bitcoin Core after Satoshi Nakamoto stepped back, was a strong advocate for increasing the block size limit and supported Bitcoin Cash. Other supporters of Bitcoin Cash included Roger Ver, Jihan Wu (Co-founder of Bitmain), Craig Wright, and Calvin Ayre.
On the other hand, prominent supporters of Bitcoin, who favored maintaining the smaller block size, included Adam Back, Gregory Maxwell, Wladimir van der Laan, and Pieter Wuille.
https://bitcointalk.org/index.php?topic=2040221.0 
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin_Cash 
54.
On 25 January 2018, George Soros referred to Bitcoin as a bubble.
https://web.archive.org/web/20180414012940/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/investment-ideas/george-soros-says-bitcoin-bubble-wont-have-sharp-break-like-others/article37739168/ 
55.
Remember Laszlo, the guy who bought two pizzas in 2010? Well, on February 25, 2018, he did it again, this time using the Lightning Network, a second-layer Bitcoin application designed to enhance network scalability. Given the significant appreciation in Bitcoin's value, Laszlo paid 649,000 satoshis, or 0.00649 bitcoins.
Interestingly, the commonly shared picture of Laszlo in a red shirt with his two children around a table with two pizzas, often attributed to the 10,000 BTC pizza purchase in 2010, is actually from the Lightning Network transaction in 2018. In the picture, there is a notepad in front of the pizzas with the code "7241 A8C1," which is the first and last four characters of the hex string of the transaction. This code proved he paid the invoice, as a friend from London acted as a middleman, accepting the Lightning payment and facilitating the real purchase with the local pizza shop.
https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2018-February/001044.html 
56.
On November 26, 2018, Ohio became the first US state to allow taxes to be paid in Bitcoin. At that point, companies in the state were able to pay a variety of taxes, including sales tax, employee withholding tax, and public utilities tax, with BTC.
https://www.coindesk.com/markets/2018/11/26/ohio-becomes-first-us-state-to-allow-taxes-to-be-paid-in-bitcoin/ 
57.
In September 2019, Bitcoin's network hash rate reached a historic milestone of 100 quintillion hashes (100 EH/s). To put that into perspective, the combined hash rate of all 2 billion PCs and 3 billion smartphones in 2019 would be approximately 0.002003 EH/s. Thus, at that time, the Bitcoin network was 50,000 times more powerful than all the PCs and smartphones in the world combined.
https://cointelegraph.com/news/bitcoin-hash-rate-to-hit-a-whopping-100-quintillion-for-the-first-time 
58.
On August 11, 2020, MicroStrategy, the Nasdaq-listed business intelligence company, became the first publicly traded company to buy Bitcoin as part of its capital allocation strategy. The company purchased 21,454 bitcoins and announced its plan to buy Bitcoin as a way to avoid inflation.
"This investment reflects our belief that Bitcoin, as the world's most widely-adopted cryptocurrency, is a dependable store of value and an attractive investment asset with more long-term appreciation potential than holding cash," said CEO Michael J. Saylor.
https://www.theblock.co/linked/74534/microstrategy-becomes-first-listed-company-to-buy-bitcoin 
https://web.archive.org/web/20200918170616/ https://www.microstrategy.com/us/company/press/microstrategy-adopts-bitcoin-as-primary-treasury-reserve-asset 
59.
On February 19, 2021, Bitcoin's market cap reached $1 trillion for the first time. It took Bitcoin just 12 years to grow from an academic whitepaper to a $1 trillion decentralized network, becoming the eighth tradable asset to boast a thirteen-figure market cap at that time. By contrast, it took Microsoft 45 years for its capitalization to exceed $1 trillion, Amazon 27 years, and Google to achieve the $1 trillion mark in just 22 years.
https://cointelegraph.com/news/bitcoin-s-market-cap-breaks-1-trillion-after-tripling-in-three-months 
60.
On June 9, 2021, El Salvador became the first country in the world to adopt Bitcoin as legal tender. The Legislative Assembly of El Salvador voted to pass the Bitcoin Law, making Bitcoin a legal form of currency in the country, with a majority vote of 62 out of 84 deputies in favor.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin_in_El_Salvador 
 
61.
In January 2022, the government of Kazakhstan removed price caps on liquefied petroleum gas used for car fuel to align with market conditions, causing the price to double overnight and sparking violent protests across the country. In response, the state-owned Kazakhtelecom, in a totalitarian decision, shut down the nation's internet. This shutdown significantly impacted major Bitcoin mining pools in the region.
A comparison of mining pool hash rates from half a day before the internet shutdown and after indicated a decline in rates for several mining pools. According to data compiled by YCharts.com, the Bitcoin network's overall hash rate declined by 13.4% in the hours following the shutdown, dropping from about 205,000 Peta hash per second (PH/s) to 177,330 PH/s. Kazakhstan accounts for 18% of the Bitcoin network's hash activity.
https://cointelegraph.com/news/kazakh-government-resigns-shuts-down-internet-amid-protests-causing-bitcoin-network-hash-rate-to-tumble-13-4 
https://www.theblock.co/post/129312/bitcoin-mining-pool-hashrates-fall-amid-kazakhstan-internet-shutdown 
62.
On April 27, 2022, The Central African Republic (CAR) became the second country to approve Bitcoin as legal tender.
https://www.reuters.com/world/africa/central-african-republic-adopts-bitcoin-an-official-currency-2022-04-27/ 
63.
On April 29, 2022, Goldman Sachs offered its first Bitcoin-backed loan. This financial product allows Bitcoin owners to borrow fiat currency, such as the US dollar, by pledging their BTC as collateral to the bank. The underlying volatility of Bitcoin can make these loans risky. If the price of Bitcoin drops significantly, borrowers may be required to increase their collateral to maintain the loan, otherwise, they risk getting liquidated.
https://cointelegraph.com/news/goldman-sachs-offers-first-bitcoin-backed-loan-as-wall-street-embraces-crypto 
https://bitmarkets.com/en/insights/article/goldman-sachs-offered-first-bitcoin-backed-loan 
64.
On November 23rd, 2023, some users accidentally submitted 83 BTC as a gas fee. The sender's wallet was set up just minutes before the transfer, and the recipient received only 55.78 BTC of the original 139.42 BTC that was sent.
In an announcement made days after the incident, Antpool, the Bitcoin mining firm that mined block 818087 containing the transaction, stated it would refund the 83 BTC to the user. Antpool explained that its risk control system had temporarily frozen the amount when packaging the transaction.
Curiously, this was not the biggest fee ever paid in a transaction. In Bitcoin terms, the largest fee was paid in 2016 when someone accidentally sent 291 BTC in transaction fees.
https://cointelegraph.com/news/bitcoin-user-pays-3-1m-in-transition-fee-for-one-139-btc-transfer 
https://www.theblock.co/post/265387/antpool-agrees-to-refund-record-3-million-bitcoin-transaction-fee 
https://mempool.space/tx/cc455ae816e6cdafdb58d54e35d4f46d860047458eacf1c7405dc634631c570d 
65.
On January 10, 2024, The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) approved its first batch of Bitcoin spot ETFs, including applications from major firms like BlackRock. The approval came after years of debate and legal challenges. This move allows institutional investors to gain direct exposure to Bitcoin without needing to trade futures, potentially attracting significant institutional money into the market. These ETFs hold Bitcoin as their underlying asset, allowing investors to trade shares that represent the price of Bitcoin without having to directly manage it.
https://www.sec.gov/news/statement/gensler-statement-spot-bitcoin-011023 
